  "prompt": "Why can't planets be different shapes?",
  "response": "Planets form into nearly spherical shapes due to the forces of gravity and the process of planetary formation. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Gravity**: Gravity is the primary force that shapes planets. As a celestial body grows in mass, its gravity pulls all the material towards its center of mass. For a large body like a planet, the only shape that allows all parts of the surface to be equidistant from the center is a sphere. This is why planets, stars, and other massive celestial bodies are spherical.\n\n2. **Hydrostatic Equilibrium**: Planets achieve a state known as hydrostatic equilibrium, where the inward pull of gravity is balanced by the outward pressure of the material that makes up the planet. In this state, the body naturally forms a spherical shape because a sphere has the smallest surface area for a given volume, minimizing the energy of the system.\n\n3. **Planetary Formation**: Planets form from the accumulation of material in a protoplanetary disk around a young star. As small particles collide and stick together, they form larger bodies called planetesimals. These planetesimals continue to collide and merge, growing larger over time. The more massive the body becomes, the stronger its gravity, which pulls it into a more spherical shape.\n\n4. **Rotation**: While planets are nearly spherical, they can be slightly flattened at the poles and bulge at the equator due to rotation. This is known as an oblate spheroid shape. For example, Earth is slightly flattened at the poles and has an equatorial bulge due to its rotation.\n\n5. **Exceptions**: There are exceptions in the solar system, like some smaller bodies that do not have enough mass to achieve hydrostatic equilibrium. For instance, asteroids and small moons can have irregular shapes because their gravity is not strong enough to overcome their structural rigidity.\n\nIn summary, the combination of gravity, hydrostatic equilibrium, and the process of planetary formation results in planets being nearly spherical. Any deviation from a perfect sphere is usually due to rotation or, in the case of smaller bodies, insufficient mass to achieve a spherical shape.",
